As Katie wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/15/2004 at 21:56:40 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Someone stated that there is a 70% chance of rain every day and 
that 
>what happens one day will not affect the next.  What are the 
chances 
>that we will get 15 days of rain in a 30 day month?
>
>[Difficulty]
>I thought I had the right answer 70% x (15/30) = 35% chance but I 
>was told I was wrong.  Can you explain why I was wrong? What did I 
>do wrong?  I am confused.
>
>[Thoughts]
>70% x (15/30) =
> 70% x 1/2 = 35%

If you mean EXACTLY 15 days and no more or less the probability is 
calculated from

   C(30,15) x 0.7^15 x 0.3^15  =  0.0105669

This is known as binomial probability and applies when you have a 
given number of independent 'trials' with a constant probability 
of 'success' at each trial.


